          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, that combination you're describing — disrupted sleep, lost appetite, dreading runs, and an elevated resting HR — that's your body sending a pretty clear signal, and I want to make sure we take it seriously together.\n\nBefore we talk training, I want to check in on you as a person, not just as a runner. How are you doing beyond the running? Sometimes that kind of full-body fatigue has roots outside of training too.\n\n---\n\nHere's what I want to share with you, and I'd love to know what you already think is going on first — **what's your read on why your body is feeling this way right now?**\n\n*(Take a moment with that, then read on.)*\n\nWhat you're describing maps closely onto **overreaching** — a state where accumulated training stress has outpaced your body's ability to recover. The elevated resting HR alone is one of the most reliable early warning signs coaches watch for. Paired with sleep disruption, appetite loss, and that dread feeling, this isn't just tiredness. It's your physiology asking for a different input.\n\nHere's the counterintuitive part, and I want to be honest with you about it: **pushing through this doesn't protect your half marathon — it puts it at risk.** Overreaching that goes unaddressed can slide into full overtraining syndrome, which can sideline a runner for weeks or months, not days. A well-timed reduction now is genuinely the faster path to that start line in July.\n\nYou have **10 weeks**, which is actually enough runway to do this right. A recovery week now doesn't erase your fitness — aerobic adaptations are remarkably durable. What erodes fitness is injury, illness, or a body that's too depleted to absorb quality work.\n\n---\n\n**What I'd suggest considering this week:**\n\n- Drop volume to around 25–28 km, keeping efforts easy (5:50–6:27/km) — no tempo, no intervals\n- Cap your long run at 10–11 km, easy effort\n- Treat sleep as your primary training variable this week — it's doing more for your half marathon than any workout right now\n\nI'd also gently recommend checking in with a doctor or sports medicine professional, especially given the appetite changes and the duration of the sleep disruption. That's outside my lane to assess, and you deserve a proper look.\n\n---\n\nOne thing I want you to hold onto: **the fitness you've built is real.** Three weeks of solid training, a tempo session at exactly the right pace, long runs building steadily — that doesn't disappear. It's banked. A recovery week is how you get to actually use it.\n\nWhat feels most difficult about pulling back this week — is it the time pressure, or something else?"
        }
      ],
